Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", NotesViewModel.Current.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        NotesViewModel.Current.DraftText =
            Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", NotesViewModel.Current.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**2. In your ViewModel, expose `DraftText` with change notification:**

```csharp
public partial class NotesViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    public static NotesViewModel Current { get; set; } = null!;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;
}
```

**3. Bind it in your XAML:**

```xml
<Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
```

### Key things to know

| Point | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Save in **`OnStopped`** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Also save in **`OnDestroying`** | Android back-button can skip `Stopped` |
| **Don't** save in `OnDeactivated` | That fires for dialogs/split-screen — too noisy |
| `Resumed` **won't** fire on first launch | Initial sequence is `Created → Activated` |
| Keep handlers **fast** (<2s) | Avoids ANR on Android / watchdog kills on iOS |

`Preferences` is ideal here since draft text is small. For larger state (images, rich documents), serialize to a file instead.
